European inflation slipped on food
The accelerating inflation measured in the Eurozone is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
The November price increase in the 13 countries of the euro zone was greater than expected, after the 2.6 percent in October, annual inflation of 3.1 percent was registered, the Union&#39;s statistical office in Luxembourg reported.
The official forecast made only 3 percent likely, Bloomberg reported.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the American, British and Canadian central banks, did not cut the key interest rate, saying that the reduction would lead to the formation of an inflationary spiral together with rising commodity prices and easing unemployment.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below two percent, but close to it.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the trap of twenty-two: inflation must be &quot;talked down&quot; so that it does not have to act on this issue later.
In Germany, the November inflation rate of 3.3 percent is considered a twelve-year record; In Spain, it rose to 4.1 from 3.6.
Eurozone inflation was driven high by rising food and energy prices.
Wheat futures were up 88 percent, and soybean prices also hit their highest since 1973.
You also had to pay significantly more for cooking oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil has increased by 52 percent this year, and last month a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from this year&#39;s 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but will decrease to 1.9 in 2009.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation level will remain around 3 percent in the next 3-4 months, but the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice during 2008.
