Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco raised it by almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trade triangle maintained last year&#39;s average price increase of 16 percent, with the difference that the VAT did not increase this year.
An article from Napi Gesdaság
This year, Napi&#39;s usual Christmas basket in the Budaörs shopping triangle increased by an average of 16 percent, but in all hypermarkets the value increased by well over a thousand forints.
Since the prices in grocery stores already &quot;flew away&quot; in December last year, there was no drastic price increase compared to the previous high base.
But it is obviously terrifying for consumers that what they could get for less than nine thousand forints last year, now they can&#39;t even get it for ten thousand.
Napi&#39;s basket exceeded the psychological limit of 10,000 forints in the analyzed hypermarkets by at least HUF 91.
The highest basket value was HUF 10,573.
(In 2003, the basket cost HUF 6,800.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year&#39;s level, but turkey breast fillets, walnuts and poppy seeds also rose in price.
The prices of flour and bread in stores followed the data of the KSH, although we found a kilogram of bread at Auchan for HUF 139.
The competition did not lower the price of the product below HUF 200.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of the two-liter returnable bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so even with the deposit fee, they only asked for 257 forints for the product.
However, this year, Auchan was the most expensive in Napi&#39;s basket, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, compared to last year&#39;s Christmas prices, Cora increased the prices in the Napi basket by 15 percent, while Tesco and Auchan increased by 18 percent each.
Comparing last year&#39;s most expensive and this year&#39;s cheapest basket value, the difference was 12 percent, while the increase between last year&#39;s cheapest and this year&#39;s most expensive is 21 percent.
The increase was HUF 1,480 on average.
Last year, the average price increase came to HUF 1,206, so that the VAT increase had an impact on prices last Christmas.
It was precisely this process that disrupted trade, as it was obvious that the department stores could not decide how much margin to apply to each product, as they were unable to calculate what effect the price change would have on consumption.
(If the rotation speed of a product is poorly planned by the trader, it can seriously benefit from the margin adjusted to the traffic intensity.)
Due to the VAT, the price increase of Napi&#39;s basket was so extreme last year that the most expensive was HUF 1,720 more than the 2006 value, while the price difference for the cheapest was only HUF 844.
This year, this extreme did not show itself, since the most expensive one was HUF 1,630 more than last year, and the cheapest also went up by HUF 1,284.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months, the prices of daily consumer goods in hypermarkets rose by more than 30 percent.
(By the way, this does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: the statistical office measured a price increase of more than 30 percent in the case of some basic foodstuffs in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour as well as with eggs.)
According to Napi kosara, this seems almost impossible for the latter, since the price level of the already quite expensive product last year produced a price increase of just over 10 percent even in the worst case.
The flour suppliers seem to be in a stronger position than the egg suppliers, and the supermarkets also managed to beat the drastic price increase.
In the commercial golden triangle, the hypers do not complain, they constantly report a good year.
According to our experience, the majority of customers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
They buy quantities of everything, and carry long-lasting food in pallets.
On Wednesday morning, serious queues formed in front of the cash registers in all three stores, because the number of visitors suddenly increased.
But we know that traffic is less in the countryside, and more multinationals complain to research companies that their income falls short of their plans, not only in the case of food, but also in the case of consumer durables.
Many places save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals, mainly due to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
The sanitary conditions of the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, and the overload of the staff are not conducive to stopping infections, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, they also save on disinfectants.
An MRSA infection was recently diagnosed in the trauma department of the János hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected in a man admitted after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred in the same location earlier this year.
The victim of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but soon after he had to return with an MRSA infection, and since then an important operation could not be performed because of the bacteria in his body.
This year, until December 10, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multiresistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, head of department at the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multiresistant pathogens were definitely registered in hospitals, the rest are unknown.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry the bacterium Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their noses without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. sore throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be easily cured.
However, when antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develop into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics, which can spread rapidly in inappropriate hospital conditions.
Primarily when the immune system is temporarily or permanently malfunctioning, it can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or blood poisoning - sepsis - in weakened, elderly or underweight patients.
According to the medical director of János hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections are part of the daily practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only not there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where the presence of the pathogen is not investigated.
Resistant to antibiotics
&quot;We isolate such patients, the nursing staff wears rubber gloves and masks, and we have the right antibiotics to treat them,&quot; said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are examined from the outset to see if MRSA is present in their bodies, but infection cannot always be avoided even in this way.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current domestic hospital conditions and conditions are not favorable for preventing the development and spread of multiresistant pathogens, claims Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor incoming patients and isolate patients carrying MRSA immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these tests also plays a role in this.
Most cases thus come to light when the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the chief physician of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
It is necessary to strive for antibiotic therapy to be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent the development of resistance to the drugs, but hospitals do not comply with this in all cases.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and primary care, said Karolina Böröcz.
They save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often spread from one patient to another by healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is spread by droplet infection and contact, but in domestic hospital conditions, it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, the wards are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, even though from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, Karolina Böröcz noted, it can also be seen that in hospitals with unfavorable financial conditions, they save on disinfectants, there are few nurses, and many patients, so the chance of infections is even greater.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate precautions are observed, there are demonstrably fewer such infections, or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection causes huge expenses for health insurance companies, so they are fighting it everywhere.
In England, e.g. the government included the prevention and reduction of MRSA in its program.
According to the indications, the program is successful, based on the published data, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
Among the priorities of the European Center for Disease Prevention (ECDC) is the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by such pathogens.
