Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
According to the Minister of Environment and Water Affairs Gábor Fodor, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and on Wednesday, after the official opening, the discussion of the international climate regime after 2012 will continue with the discussion of the ministers.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which provides for efforts to follow the emission reduction period set by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
Currently, there is a heated debate about this between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also indicated that it does not currently wish to discuss exact numbers, although it is leaning towards an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
Another big question of the conference is whether the developed countries undertake, in addition to reducing emissions, to provide both material and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on the subsidies to be provided to developing countries.
The support fund, which is provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, expected to be part of the UN&#39;s Global Environmental Protection Fund (GEF), according to Market and Profit.
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Water Affairs Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU&#39;s efforts to maintain its role as a flagship in global climate protection efforts and to promote the creation of a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister explained that the EU undertakes to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent compared to the 1990 level by 2020, regardless of the success of concluding the &quot;post-2012 agreement&quot;, and is ready to undertake a reduction of up to 30 percent, in the event that the other large developed regions of the world, as well as developing countries, are also willing to undertake obligations in accordance with their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that in 1997, the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol set a total reduction of 5.2 percent, within which the EU - then still 15 member states - undertook minus 8 percent.
The Hungarian obligation is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent in 1985-87. compared to the period between, which our country will fulfill. - reminds the press release of the Ministry of Environmental Protection.
The stakes are high in Bali, as the long-term international climate policy agreement must be concluded within two years, otherwise its entry into force would surely be postponed until after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the necessity of which was pointed out by the IPCC, the UN Nobel Peace Prize-winning international scientific body dealing with climate change, in its latest report.
This would delay emission reductions and make it inevitable that the Earth&#39;s average temperature would rise above 2 degrees Celsius, which would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences, according to scientists.
The British Army is recruiting on YouTube
British army units are posting footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video sharing site to promote themselves.
The British Air Force (RAF) was the first to get onto YouTube: the special forces operating in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of their operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reported.
These recordings, taken with a miniature camera mounted on a helmet, are checked at the air force&#39;s operational headquarters in Kandahar, and then sent to London, where the Hungarians upload them to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
139 recordings of Air Force soldiers have already been uploaded to the Internet in this form, and their &quot;channel&quot; has been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defense registered as &quot;defenceheadquarters&quot; in the spring of 2007 and publishes videos of both Iraq and Afghanistan operations, while the British Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
The Air Force originally put up the videos for recruiting purposes, and the Defense Department says it&#39;s also good for informing the general public about the true purpose of the military&#39;s presence abroad.
Defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC that the propaganda published in this form costs almost nothing compared to traditional television recruitment advertisements, but it inevitably carries some political message, as it justifies the legitimacy of military actions decided by the government in a special way.
The Americans made a game
The army is also troubled by the fact that, in addition to carefully edited, censored footage, amateur videos are also uploaded to the sharing site, which for example show the death of soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, &quot;official&quot; propaganda films, the officers talk as much as possible about the losses, but do not show them the bloody side of the fight.
By the way, many videos from the battlefields in Iraq and Afghanistan have already appeared on the Internet, which were made during live deployments, but the British army only recently found out about them.
The Americans recruit in a slightly different way, with the free-to-download shooting game called America&#39;s Army, in which the player can get into the shoes of the soldiers in a more or less realistic simulation.
