The holiday is not a red letter everywhere
In Hungary, the law clearly indicates the days marked in red, and it has already become common practice to rearrange working days around holidays, of which there will be fewer next year.
The holiday is not the same in the EU and America either.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and state holidays and public holidays.
Public holidays are mostly associated with church holidays and significant historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year here: the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are both holidays - the latter just so that New Year&#39;s Eve people can relax.
By the way, we have a total of eleven red-letter holidays throughout the year.
March 15 commemorating the 1848 revolution and October 23, as well as the commemoration day of the 1956 revolution, are national holidays.
On August 20, we celebrate the founding of the state, on May 1, we celebrate work, and on November 1 and 2, we remember our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, Easter, Pentecost and Christmas are two-day holidays.
Since, according to the calendar, our state, national or even religious holidays rarely fall on the weekend, it has become a practice to move the working day in cases where we would only work one day before or after the red letter holiday.
It is true that the price of extended weekends is that we do not stay away from work and school on the preceding Saturdays.
For many years, the Minister of Labor has regulated in a separate decree when exactly the day immediately preceding or following the holiday must be worked.
The legislation covers all employers and their employees, public employees and those in public service.
However, it does not affect service companies and institutions that operate without interruption and, due to their purpose, also operate on public holidays.
This year, the work schedule will only be changed around the year-end holidays: from December 24, life in the country will almost stop, as experience shows that the majority of people &quot;skip&quot; the days between Christmas and New Year&#39;s Eve, or use their saved vacation time for this purpose.
Next year, several of our holidays will fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer working day shifts than this year.
First, the calendar changes around Labor Day, so that workers can stay at home for four consecutive days.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2, can be a day of rest.
The other transfer is related to the October 23 holiday: you will have to work on October 18, Saturday, instead of Friday the 24th.
However, the end of the year can be spent completely in the spirit of the holiday next year, since from December 24 almost everywhere there will be a non-stop break, even if New Year&#39;s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six discouraging little things you can do to annoy your colleagues
E-mails that we forget to send, voicemail messages that we never receive, innocent lies that we almost don&#39;t even notice anymore: these &quot;color&quot; the everyday at work.
It is a question of whether you get used to small inconveniences or whether you put on the gloves and consciously avoid situations that are misunderstood and cause annoyance to others.
Tips.
&quot;Sorry, I forgot to tell you that I was contacted by the marketing department,&quot; says one of your colleagues.
How did you miss a meeting because of this?
At best, you&#39;ll regret it and try to make it right, maybe call the marketing department to tell them you forgot to deliver the message (this is the less common solution).
Most of the time, the matter is settled with an apology.
Before making an awkward apology, it&#39;s worth thinking about what you can do to make your colleagues uncomfortable, and make a conscious effort to avoid it.
Borrowing something you don&#39;t own?
There is nothing more annoying than when you reach for a document, stationery or your phone, and it is nowhere to be found.
Do you remember that yesterday you put your stapler on the table, but in the morning it was broken?
Perhaps you discover your lost pen on the desk of one of your colleagues?
Don&#39;t take anything from your colleagues without asking, because they will rightfully be angry with you for stealing their property.
Don&#39;t put office envelopes or post-it notes in your pocket, because it can be unpleasant if it runs out before time, and you need it right away.
Do you gossip about your colleagues&#39; private lives?
There is no good way to stop a rumor that is already spreading.
Who, with whom, what did he do?
Where and why?
Don&#39;t share your information (assumptions) about the private lives of your colleagues!
If one of them shares their innermost secrets with you, don&#39;t abuse their trust!
Bury what you heard and do not discuss it with your colleagues in your absence, even if others also know about the things your colleague is wearing.
Are you calling in sick for no reason?
When you call the office and call in sick citing a splitting headache because you feel bad or feel like you&#39;d rather rest that day; think about the fact that someone else has to do your work, urgent tasks, and deadline tasks for you.
Don&#39;t mess with your colleagues!
If you know in advance that you will not be in the office the next day, or something may come up that requires you to stay at home, let your colleagues and your boss know that you are not there the next day.
Burping, giggling, calling
Are you engrossed in your work, but the giggles of your colleagues pull you out of it?
Have you inadvertently overheard a phone conversation that would have been better left unheard?
Do not disturb your colleagues by humming, singing, talking loudly (which you carry on above their heads), nor by stomping your feet, continuous swearing, or loud displeasure.
All of these can be confusing, even if they don&#39;t delve into a particular project (writing, planning, organization).
Do you blame others for mistakes?
If you don&#39;t have time for something, you forgot to send an important letter or message, don&#39;t blame someone else for your forgetfulness!
Do not refer to the chaos in the office or your loud colleagues!
Admit it if you made a mistake and someone else suffered a disadvantage from it, and eliminate the flaw!
Ask how you can correct your mistake, make up for the omission!
Do you feel too at home in the office?
Teddy bear pants and slippers: comfortable to wear at home, but not for the office!
Don&#39;t wear comfortable casual clothes even if your job allows it!
Don&#39;t be a slob, respect your colleagues and yourself by going to the office in casual clothes - if your job requires it, neatly and elegantly!
