So everything is fine (?).
hvg.hu asked Balázs Zságer.
hvg.hu: This new hit song now raises the question: how much of the layered music you play is left?
Balázs Zságer: The definition of layered music doesn&#39;t mean much to me.
I think there are two types of light music castes; not mainstream and underground, not alternative and pop, but commercial and honest.
The so-called alternative, underground music can also be flat, meaningless and just as well prepared for sale, which makes them commercial.
But a good pop song can also come from honest motives.
The welcoming attitude also works in this spirit, regardless of language and national borders.
hvg.hu: Do you see a difference in the openness of Hungarian and foreign audiences to music?
Zs.B.: Abroad, especially to the west of us, there are greater traditions of light music.
Not only the ten- and twenty-year-old age group go to concerts there, but also older people.
They are more likely to monitor the changes in popular music around them, because they also consider it a part of contemporary culture.
hvg.hu: What is the role of the audience in your work?
Does it matter who, where, how many people listen to your music?
Zs.B.: Of course, it feels good that more and more people are coming to our concerts.
