The banks want to solve the crisis
The American Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the financial market crisis.
In this way, more than a hundred billion dollars enter the financial markets through the stock exchanges.
On these exchanges, the bank raises the interest rate for which they are ready to lend money.
For example, the US Fed releases forty billion dollars to the stock market and makes another twenty-four billion available to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the September 11th attacks that the central banks of each country have agreed on a coordinated procedure to prevent or reduce the consequences of the financial crisis.
&quot;This move should solve the economy&#39;s biggest problems, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks can lend,&quot; Bernard Baumohl of the Economic Outlook Group wrote in a report to clients.
&quot;Coordinated action by central banks in the United States reduced the probability of a recession from 65 percent to about fifty percent,&quot; Baumohl added in his report.
Banks, primarily in the United States, have already lost sixty billion dollars due to unpaid loans.
