&quot;Central banks can really fear what may come next if they decide to take such a course,&quot; said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
It seems like the situation is really bad,&quot; he added.
Central banks are afraid that if the banks themselves have difficulty accessing loans, they will also make loans more expensive to their customers.
This would reduce demand and push the US economy into recession with possible consequences for economic growth around the world.
