Under the Spanish, Cuba was the bastion of their American conquests.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye had ever seen.
Havana became a storehouse and transshipment point for treasure that the Spanish looted in the Americas and transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Nacional Hotel was built at the end of the 20s.
It was built by Lucky Luciano, one of the bosses of the American mafia, because everything that was considered a crime in the USA (primarily alcohol) was welcomed in Cuba, and drugs, gambling, and prostitution were supported.
Among his guests were, for example
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
High-rise buildings were built in Havana, and cars that became cult symbols of the 1950s drove on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought an estate in San Francisco de Paula, not far from Havana, and had his own yacht in Cojímar.
The walls of Bodeguita del Medio are decorated with the signatures of American show business stars and politicians.
