The most famous places are not avoided by the majority of visitors to Cuba.
So it is not necessary to write too much about Varader or Havana.
Perhaps we should just remind you that there is a museum on the aforementioned Hemingway estate, and anyone who loves the writer should not miss visiting this museum.
The Viňales Valley is one of the most picturesque parts of Cuba in the western part of the island.
Lush vegetation grows from limestone.
Limestone formations, limestone cones and rocks rise steeply from the bottom of the valley and fertile soil has accumulated in their hollows, thanks to which even the weathered cliffs are covered with dense vegetation.
The valley is where perhaps the best quality Cuban tobacco is grown.
You can see its final form when you visit one of the Havana cigar factories.
Some may also find it interesting that Major Zeman&#39;s Chilean episode was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonization of the island.
The slave and sugar trade brought fame and glory.
The economy took shape in the beauty and monumentality of the not very big city.
The colonial Spanish architecture, significantly influenced by later French settlers, has changed almost nothing in four centuries.
Trinidad, between the Escambray plain and the sea, is such a secluded place that even in the 50s of the last century there were no roads connecting this region with the rest of the country.
That certain isolation helped him remain an outsider.
Nothing was built there, so it was not demolished, everyone was happy to have a roof over their heads.
If you have more than an afternoon in Trinidad, it is worth visiting the interesting places in the area, such as the Playa Ancón beach or the Valley of the Sugar Mills.
And in the evening, you should go to the Casa de la Música, which comes alive after dark, where the music only quietens down in the morning.
Baracoa
The small town in the eastern part of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful town.
This opinion is probably influenced by the road itself.
Both roads leading from Guantanamo have to overcome high and rugged mountains, they lead through nature that is hardly affected by human activity.
Due to its untouched nature, the eastern peninsula of Cuba has been added to the World Heritage List by UNESCO.
The best chocolate is made here, there is a Columbus cross in the church (in reality it was made a hundred years after Columbus sailed) and from the hill where the former castle stood and today the El Castillo hotel stands, you can see some table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Meastro plain, the Bay of Pigs and the Isla de Pinos, the Tropicana cabaret, the Caridad del Cobra, the patron saint of Cuba, Santeria, an African religion practiced by the descendants of former slaves, and a lot of it. can be written.
