According to the first data of the investigation launched by the General Inspection Body of the National Police (IGPN), on Sunday, a few minutes after 5:00 p.m., a police car was driving on rue Louise-Michel in Villiers-le-Bel.
&quot;The car was on patrol, so it was not participating in an action. It was traveling at a speed of 40-50 km/h, without sounding the siren,&quot; we learned from a police source.
The two youths without helmets were driving at &quot;high speed&quot; with a green Kawasaki motorcycle, &quot;which is not included in the official register and therefore cannot be used in road traffic&quot; (see below).
&quot;Because they didn&#39;t follow the right-hand rule, the motorbike hit the left side of the police car,&quot; says a policeman.
The results of the alcohol test on the vehicle&#39;s passengers were negative.
The fact that the front of the car is dented, the windshield is cracked in the shape of a star, and the bumper is torn off clearly shows the force of the collision.
Pontoise&#39;s public prosecutor, Marie-Thérèse de Givry, said in an extraordinary announcement yesterday morning that she had entrusted the IGPN and the Val-D&#39;Oise County Public Security Directorate with the investigation, which was opened &quot;for manslaughter by negligence and failure to render assistance&quot;.
In the afternoon, the prosecutor said at a press conference that at the current stage of the IGPN&#39;s investigation, the responsibility of the police can be ruled out.
According to the prosecutor, the three witnesses of the accident, interviewed on Sunday evening, confirmed &quot;the report of the police, according to which the scooter arrived relatively quickly from the left side of the police car&quot;.
Yesterday, a strip, no doubt drawn by the footrests on the road, showed that the two vehicles got stuck and drove together for a while until the police car managed to brake.
The vehicles were impounded for technical inspection.
The medical examination of the bodies of the two victims was carried out yesterday.
What happened right after that?
Rumors spread like wildfire in Villiers-le-Bel yesterday that the police quickly left the scene without offering help to the two youths.
In this regard, the IGPN expresses caution, but rules out that the police made &quot;any serious mistakes&quot;.
&quot;This is the most difficult part of the investigation, which requires an even more thorough investigation and increased caution during this,&quot; we learned from a police source.
Libération met with an eyewitness who described the minutes after the accident.
One of the windows of his apartment looks right at the site.
&quot;My cousin, who is a hospital nurse, and I immediately went downstairs to try to revive them,&quot; the witness said.
&quot;There was nothing more we could do.&quot;
He then noticed &quot;a policeman who was completely confused and limping.
The other two tried to revive one of the young people, and the fourth made a phone call.
The tension among those present increased as the hopeless situation of the two young people became apparent, so the arriving police officers took their colleagues away from the scene by car.
We also know from the witness&#39; statement that the ambulance arrived &quot;about 20 minutes after the police left.&quot;
Heart massage was also used, but to no avail.
&quot;I wouldn&#39;t say that the police didn&#39;t try to help the young people.
The young people did get help.
Firefighters arrived on the scene immediately.
They did everything to save them,&quot; the prosecutor emphasized.
