Spectacular repair on the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) had to work for more than seven hours in space to perform a spectacular repair of a torn solar panel essential to the station&#39;s scientific activities.
This dangerous spacewalk turned out to be a record in several ways: the repair took a very long time, there was very little time to plan it, and it had to be done far from the living modules, with tools &quot;do-it-yourself&quot; by the astronauts.
The problem occurred on Tuesday when astronauts detached the Harmony module from Discovery. It is a giant cylindrical feature that will soon be the site of scientific laboratory activities in Europe and Japan (see box).
This module is a kind of gateway to the laboratory modules.
However, you have to take care of their power supply.
The second task of the crew was therefore to move one of the modules, which was already on the ISS, generating electricity with the help of 17.5-ton solar panels to its final location.
The crew then began opening the module&#39;s 76-meter-wide solar panels.
At that time, one of the boards that could be folded like an accordion was damaged by a stuck cable about 1 meter long.
In order to avoid further damage, the opening of the board was not continued.
The astronauts were originally tasked with doing a walk-through of the space shuttle Discovery and then repairing another solar array with a failed rotation system. Instead, they had to devote all their time to repairing the damaged solar panel.
Scott Parazynski was chosen to perform the stunt while hanging from the space shuttle&#39;s 30-meter robotic arm attached to the station&#39;s crane.
He is one of NASA&#39;s best &quot;spacewalkers&quot;.
He is tall, strong, extremely skilled, has a muscular upper body and long arms.
The 46-year-old man with a doctor&#39;s degree had to &quot;operate&quot; on the &quot;damaged&quot; solar panel.
After carefully assessing the damage, he cut the faulty cable and secured the damaged area with some &quot;rails&quot;.
He was assisted in his work by another &quot;spacewalker&quot; who remained near the safe passage, as well as the other astronauts from inside, including crew captain Peggy Whitson.
The tool he used, a mini-hockey stick insulated against the hundreds of volts of solar panels, was invented and &quot;homemade&quot; by the station&#39;s astronauts.
After completing the operation, Scott Parazynski waited until his companions fully opened the board before packing up his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts had a half-day rest, and today seven returned to the space shuttle Discovery to begin the return home scheduled for Wednesday.
