The status quo remains
Sunday&#39;s elections do not promise any big surprises: the vast majority of Russians will vote for President Putin&#39;s party, United Russia.
This shows the Russians&#39; need for stability, one might say arbitrary governance, after a heavily manipulated campaign.
Today, i.e. three days before the parliamentary elections, Russian President Vladimir Putin addresses the voters in a televised message via public service channels, which has already been recorded, but its content is still secret.
Putin leads the list of candidates for the pro-Kremlin party United Russia, which is expected to win a landslide victory in the election.
At the reception of the foreign ambassadors yesterday, the behavior of the head of state did not reveal anything: he only made another outburst against the interventions of Western countries, which was a favorite topic during the campaign.
&quot;We know the price of real democracy, so we want honest, absolutely transparent and open elections, without any violation of the law,&quot; he added.
However, according to the opposition, this is by no means the case.
The opposition has condemned the campaign, which they say pressured voters.
The head of the Communist Party, Gennady Zyuganov, claims that &quot;there was no such dirty election in Russia even during Yeltsin&#39;s time&quot;.
After last weekend&#39;s protests were crushed, former world chess champion Garry Kasparov was sentenced to five days in jail for an unauthorized demonstration and is still barred from visiting, according to his lawyer.
&quot;Russians still think like &#39;homo sovieticus&#39;&quot;
Predictable election results raise two even more obvious questions:
- Who will succeed Putin as the head of state?
The date of the first round of the presidential election was published in the official newspaper yesterday, which will be March 2, 2008, and the candidates can indicate their intention to run until December 23.
Since Vladimir Putin was elected in 2000 and 2004, his mandate cannot be extended any further.
However, there is no other successor on the horizon.
- What role does Putin play from March?
Will he be prime minister?
Or will he, as the leader of the all-powerful United Russia party and the parliamentary majority, decide on the government and the president?
Whatever happens, the outgoing government wins both the parliamentary and presidential elections.
This has become a tradition.
&quot;Russians still think like &#39;homo sovieticus&#39;: they don&#39;t feel like they can control their destiny,&quot; says sociologist Lev Gudkov, director of the independent Levada Center.
Nikolaj Koposzov, a historian at the University of St. Petersburg, goes even further than this: according to his theory, the country became Christian five hundred years later than Europe, so the development of civil society is delayed. And the traditional community spirit hindered the development of individualism.
After the liberal reforms of the 1990s, &quot;Putin reverted to the paternalistic model, which suited the people perfectly. All the more so, since this new kind of paternalism was not associated with intimidation, but with a certain economic prosperity,&quot; Maria Lipman, a staff member of the Carnegie Foundation, believes. .
Today, Russians &quot;voluntarily reject personal responsibility&quot;, which quickly became apparent after the collapse of the Soviet Union.
&quot;Why should we think?&quot;
The phenomenon affects all layers of society, even the business world.
The administrative elite is interested in maintaining the current situation: the local lists of United Russia are headed by 65 governors who come from the leaders of the 85 Russian regions.
Freedom imported from the West often embodies chaos, as it did in the 90s.
The public prefers stability.
In this spirit, Russians do not vote for extreme parties either.
Tamara Cherednichenko, a 54-year-old teacher, concludes: &quot;Why should we think?
The people in power aren&#39;t that bad, so why should we replace them?&quot;
Sad memories
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Bad Arolsen archive, which documents the fate of 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime, has become public.
The 47 million archival documents, which occupy 27 kilometers of shelves in Bad Arolsen in the province of Hesse, have so far only been researchable for &quot;humanitarian&quot; purposes, i.e., they have only provided a unique and named opportunity to view former victims or their descendants.
The eleven states managing the archive - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open the archive to researchers and historians.
After all states ratified the convention, the archive was opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the archive in Bad Arolsen will allow historians to conduct research &quot;on the transfer of prisoners, the inhabitants of the camps and the health of forced laborers,&quot; explains Reto Meistern, director of the archive managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until now, several states, including Germany, have opposed making the documents public because they contain names and therefore confidential information.
This could be, for example, the presumed homosexuality or mental disability of some deported victims.
Lists of concentration camps and arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo began to be collected after the war for practical reasons. The goal was to search for civilians who were deported or sentenced to forced labor on the basis of these, and possibly provide evidence of their internment, on the basis of which they could receive compensation.
In Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are currently engaged in the processing of tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, a part of the scientific community does not consider the opening of the archive in Bad Arolsen to be of outstanding importance.
&quot;These documents basically contain nothing new,&quot; declared Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Berlin Technical University&#39;s anti-Semitism research center, in 2006.
