Congress approves the adoption of MiFID, which entered into force on November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary proceedings - which ended today with the congressional vote approving the Senate&#39;s amendments - the government initiated a social dialogue on the regulations underlying the law, so that both could enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various groups unanimously highlighted the efforts invested by the representatives and senators in negotiations and agreements, which served to create the most favorable regulations protecting investors, as well as the detailed regulation of the companies&#39; activities, for the sake of efficient market operation.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Law, enables the modernization of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, broadening the supervisory powers of the Spanish National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new directive enables financial advisory services for specialized companies, but also for natural or legal persons, and creates a new form of financial service company (ESIS) alongside securities distribution companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies, namely the financial advisory companies (AFI).
In addition, the law increases the number of systems capable of carrying out operations involving funds, thus adding to the regulated secondary markets multilateral trading platforms and internalization systems for the execution of orders, which compete with existing stock exchange players.
Furthermore, the Law obliges investment service providers to provide market information regarding the defining aspects of their business profile, their risk taking and risk management methods, and to facilitate the control of the CNMV, they must keep a record of all performed operations.
The Economic Committee of the Congress introduced several amendments. The most important of these is that securitized debts are treated as &quot;complex&quot; financial instruments, precisely because of the high risk they represent for the investor. This was confirmed in connection with the American high-risk mortgage lending (subprime).
On the other hand, the transposition of the directive was also used to legally outline the scope of activities of those with economics and business qualifications. All this 30 years after the royal decree defining the professional functions that can only be performed by economists came into force in 1977.
And the Senate proposed the creation of new players in the financial sector, such as the intermediary&#39;s agent, who works for someone else&#39;s account, does not need a license from the CNMV, and can distribute products or acquire clients for several investment companies at the same time.
The Consumer Price Index increased by 0.5 points in November and thus reached 4.1%.
This indicator, which is taken into account by Eurostat to calculate the inflation rate of the European Union, shows the evolution of prices in Spain for the month of November.
Its release is in line with Eurostat&#39;s and the European Central Bank&#39;s strategy to provide data that is comparable to data from the United States, both in terms of timing and nature.
The preliminary indicator uses the same calculation method as for the calculation of the Unified Price Index, but the statistical modeling method is different to estimate information that is not yet available at the time of publication.
The Statistical Office emphasized that the preliminary indicator is purely informative, and therefore may differ from the final data, which will be published on December 14.
&quot;The Consumer Price Index still shows a relatively high value.&quot;
Pedro Solbes, one of the vice-presidents of the government and Minister of Economy, stated that the rise of the Consumer Price Index to 4.1% in November was only &quot;temporary&quot;, but at the same time predicted that the price index is expected to show a &quot;relatively high&quot; value in the coming months too.
In the corridors of the Parliament, Solbes confirmed that &quot;although the indicator is not really favorable&quot;, the inflation rate in Spain has remained more or less at the same level in recent years within the monetary union.
He also added that the month of November &quot;brought fewer surprises&quot; than the previous month, when the Government did not expect such a large increase.
&quot;We expected a value of around 4%,&quot; the Minister of Economy admitted regarding the data made public today.
