New fears regarding the Russian-Ukrainian gas dispute
The gas dispute between Krajina and Russia has been renewed, which may also affect the Russian fuel delivered to Western Europe.
Most of the Russian gas exported to the European Union (EU) is routed through Ukraine, and the disputes between the two nations always attract a lot of attention.
Kiev stated that if Moscow raises the gas price paid by the Ukrainians, they will also hit Russia with higher transit costs.
As a result of an earlier dispute between the two countries that erupted last year, supplies arriving in EU countries have decreased.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow is related to the attempt of the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned natural gas industry monopoly, Gazprom, to reach an agreement on the level of gas prices to be paid by Ukraine to Russia in 2008.
Gazprom has stated that it must implement a 50% price increase for gas extracted from neighboring Turkmenistan compared to the 2008 price agreement with Ukraine.
According to analysts, this could mean a 40% increase in the price of the shipment from Gazprom for Ukraine.
&quot;It is important that during the negotiations we argue in accordance with one of the most important natural gas transit countries,&quot; Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinah told the Reuters news agency.
&quot;Changes related to gas prices should definitely be connected to our discussion about the cost of transits through Ukraine (and to Western Europe).&quot;
As a result of the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom shut off the gas tap to Ukraine in January 2006.
This resulted in a domino-like decline in exports to Western Europe, which at the same time greatly pushed up prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union&#39;s gas supply.
Russia has the largest natural gas reserves in the world, but most of them are still unexplored.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own gas supply with natural gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet states in Central Asia.
NHS &#39;must check foreign workers&#39;
Scottish NHS boards must improve their criminal record checks on workers from outside Europe, a watchdog has said.
The proposal was made by Accountant General Robert Black after a foreign doctor in Scotland was linked to the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that NHS Scotland does not have accurate figures on its overseas workforce.
At the same time, in his report - through a sample of five health authorities - he also pointed out key controls that were properly carried out.
Following the attack on Glasgow Airport, the Accountant General checked the list of staff recruited from outside the European Economic Area.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi-born doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep drove into the building&#39;s main terminal.
Abdullah was one of three doctors who were questioned by video link at the Old Bailey in October over attempted car bombings in the UK.
In the case of overseas staff, NHS boards must check that they have qualifications and work experience and that they have the necessary permits to work in the UK before they start employment.
Although Scottish health boards use Disclosure Scotland to check criminal records, the agency is not authorized to obtain such information from outside the UK.
Among other things, the Auditor-General&#39;s report recommended that the commissions introduce a Criminal Records Office guide to facilitate the employer&#39;s verification processes with various overseas countries.
&quot;Although we found evidence of such checks in staff records, they are not routinely carried out,&quot; the report said.
Black says NHS Scotland performs its own pre-employment vetting process to a high standard, adding: &quot;Our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure we have up-to-date information on the number of overseas NHS staff&quot;.
Dr Peter Terry, chairman of BMA Scotland, said it was &quot;extremely unrealistic&quot; that pre-employment checks could be used to identify potential NHS staff who might commit terrorist acts in the future.
