Labor pains
Gordon Brown faces yet another gap; the exit path is unchanged
Compared to British political scandals, the current one does not seem too spicy.
No one sold their honor, no politician had his Paris hotel bills discovered, no one committed an extramarital scandal.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman secretly contributed more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) to Britain&#39;s ruling Labor Party over four years under the names of others, and that the party did not report it, is one of the things without which the besieged Gordon Brown would have been fine.
Two months ago, when the Prime Minister escaped the election, and when he recklessly questioned the intellectual capacity of the British people with his statement that opinion polls did not influence the outcome of the decision, people still hoped that Brown would ensure a strong and efficient government.
But instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly witty deputy leader of the Lib Dems, has noted, the once-feared Brown has transformed from Stalin to Mr Bean.
The botched move to rescue Northern Rock, a struggling bank, exposed regulatory weaknesses and lapses in judgment.
Sick proposals to change the tax law encouraged business interest groups to unite against the government.
The loss of the personal data of 25 million people by the tax authorities revealed an unimaginably high degree of administrative clumsiness.
Three retired generals have sparked a riot in the House of Lords protesting cuts to the army budget, saying the position of defense secretary is a part-time job.
And now here are the mysterious donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the general secretary of the Labor Party (previously chief administrative officer) has already resigned.
Those accidents don&#39;t mean Brown can&#39;t turn back on the way to the exit.
At the same time, governments can reach a point beyond which control becomes impossible.
People don&#39;t like or trust politicians, but they usually suspend disbelief when a new group comes to power.
However, as soon as it becomes clear that the prime minister is most likely not fit to take things forward and may not even stay in his post for a long time, the suspended disbelief ends: the civil service starts leaking, the cabinet ministers start briefings, the press looks for bad news; and the government will become defensive and unable to focus.
In a way, Brown is in a particularly difficult position because, unlike other political leaders, he is not considered &quot;fresh blood&quot;.
As much as he wants to deny his relationship with Tony Blair, he was still his right-hand man.
The problems surrounding Northern Rock and the IRS records, for example, are tied to decisions Brown made when he was finance minister.
And although he was not directly involved in Blair&#39;s missteps - such as the protracted investigation into the connection between the &quot;nobility for money&quot; case and political party funding - voters may rightly assume otherwise.
Although Brown&#39;s situation is indeed unpleasant, it is not as embarrassing as it seems.
The blunders are not as scary as the Tories make them out to be.
As with Mr. Bean, no one died, no one was directly infected.
And the compensation - no matter how much pain it entails - can be the creation of the trends always promised by Stalin living in Brown: reliable, solid and somewhat heavy-handed governance.
A good example is the buzz around political donations.
The mysterious Abrahams, who compares his donation to charity, said that he did not want to reveal his charity to the public.
Perhaps so, but it was not within his competence to make the decision.
The law prohibiting the anonymity of major political supporters is clear and clearly justified: the population has the right to know who is knocking on the door of the country&#39;s leaders.
Watt, who, by his own account, knew of Abrahams&#39; action but was unaware of its illegal nature, will certainly be made to sweat during interrogations; as did Jon Medleson, Labor&#39;s head of foundations, who became aware of the murky donations in October.
However, for now, there are no leads to Brown: there is no indication that he knew about these transactions, not even the fact that the huge sums were paid after Brown took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has completed half of his duties.
Although he immediately condemned the violation of the law committed by his party, his firmness was diluted by the fact that he resorted to a familiar tool; for the sake of safety, he commissioned a committee headed by a retired bishop and a judge to investigate the case.
The &quot;lesson to be learned&quot; in this story is not too complicated.
In case of violation of the law, the police is responsible.
In addition, Brown also has to put other things in order, such as the appointment of the chairman of the independent committee that has been operating without a leader for six months, which discusses public administration rules, or the promotion of the effective reform of political party financing.
This would require the hard-hat Labor Party to cooperate with the Tories and break with the special financial ties associated with the associations - this would be a tough bite for the party-loyal Brown.
But you should face some facts about the party.
According to the polls, the conservatives are currently leading by a large margin; Brown has two years to win voters back behind him; the only way to achieve victory is through impeccable integrity and strong competence.
Card sharks
Is the subprime crisis threatening America&#39;s credit card market?
If there is blood in the water, it is natural for sharks to appear nearby.
Now that the U.S. housing market is ailing, predators are focusing on the nation&#39;s credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts believe that if the mortgage crisis infects other forms of retail loans, the loss of the credit card market could reach up to 99 billion dollars.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
Both the write-off rate, indicating the proportion of uncollectible loans, and the default rate, indicating the proportion of overdue payments exceeding 30 days, increased.
HSBC last month reported a $1.4 billion loss in its U.S. consumer finance segment, partly due to financial weakness among cardholders.
However, it is still too early to panic.
Write-offs and late payments remain low.
The 3.89% delinquent ratio calculated by Moody&#39;s for the third quarter is a full percentage point lower than the historical average.
The decrease in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
The 2005 amendment to US personal insolvency rules resulted in a sudden drop in the number of people filing for insolvency, but at the same time caused a large-scale loss in the credit card market; the number of bankruptcy applications (and thus the write-off rate) is expected to increase again, regardless of whether the overall conditions for borrowing deteriorate or not.
The payment ratio, which shows the ratio of consumers&#39; monthly loan repayments, is also firm in the market.
In addition, confidence in credit card-backed securities is also quite strong, despite the paralysis in other areas of structured financing.
Dennis Moroney of the research firm TowerGroup estimates that the volume of emissions in 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
The signs of the impact of the mortgage market crisis on the credit card market are clear: consumers are increasing the debt on their credit cards to pay off their home loans.
At the same time, card issuers primarily monitor the flow of money and not the value of assets, so a fall in house prices does not necessarily cause a change in the creditworthiness of borrowers.
The situation may even be beneficial for creditors.
If the property is worth less than the value of the mortgage loan, consumers have less incentive to repay the loan; as a result, paying off credit card debt moves up the priority list.
By changing interest rates or lending limits, card issuers can adapt to changing conditions faster and more flexibly than mortgage lenders.
In theory, this should reduce the risk of sudden asset repricing.
&quot;It&#39;s unlikely that we&#39;re going to wake up one day and completely reevaluate credit,&quot; says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
If a sudden subprime crisis in the credit card market is less likely, the risk of a gradual decline is much more likely.
If falling housing prices and a slump in credit plunge America into recession, the industry will undoubtedly face a grim future.
It&#39;s worth keeping an eye on those predatory fins.
