In England, they demand the decision between Owais Shah and Ravi Bopara
Given two dilemmas, one more complicated than the other.
Who should wear England&#39;s number six jersey in Kandy, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And indirectly related to the first Test against Sri Lanka is no less important, who makes the decision?
On the one hand, the latter question is relevant because David Graveney, the chairman of the selectors, who temporarily fulfills this certain task, will help the head coach Peter Moores and the captain Michael Vaughan in the decision. And on the other hand, because the desk drawer of the England executive director, Hugh Morris, is starting to fill up with requests to reach the national, or at least one-off, position of selector.
Of the two players, the one who doesn&#39;t get the sixth batting slot draws the shorter one, but as you know, life, and especially sports, is often unfair.
It&#39;s never easy to tell what makes someone reach the top of their profession, while others can&#39;t even get past a lower level. Many times it depends on luck rather than talent.
It is not only characteristic of cricket that selection is difficult - often on a subjective basis.
Is it time for Bopara to move on?
Is it fair to Shah if this happens?
The same question can be raised in other areas of life, for example if, say, John Edwards and &quot;Tubby&quot; Banerjee, two bright, well-educated, business-savvy young executives, were presented to the decision-makers, when only one of them there is room for him.
Who can tell what level a cricketer is for without being thrown into the deep water in a more serious competition?
Of course, the data greatly influences the decision, but the options are just as important.
In a team, a player has to catch the eye of the captain at the right moment in the cricket wicket and a batsman has to get regular chances if he wants to become a big player.
Catching the selectors&#39; eye is much more complicated.
For example, several players played better than James Anderson last season, but he is considered a sure member of the team for the first test, despite the fact that Stephen Harmison, according to his own words, is in good shape and his batting is very good.
Anderson fought his way into the tour with 32 first-class wickets and 33 runs.
Chris Tremlett only hit 29, but both have had successful moments at the highest level and hope to continue in the future.
Whether Shah or Bopara will play at the Asgiriya Stadium, well that will be decided by the opinions.
This decision can make or break someone&#39;s career, but it may not have much impact on the future.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, although Gareth Batty played in every Test and performed well with five wickets and 40 useful runs, it was the then-up-and-coming Paul Collingwood who stood out and became a dominant Test cricketer, who is perhaps still underrated even today despite the fact that in Australia , scored a double hundred against the Australians.
It is likely that in their meeting at Asgiriya Stanion during today&#39;s game, Graveney, Vaughan and Moores, listening to their conservative instincts, will vote for Shah&#39;s greater experience over Bopara&#39;s young vitality and dynamism.
There are arguments for both.
His bright and successful debut in the quarters of the 88 Bombay Test speaks for Shah. Against the six of 22-year-old Bopara, seven years younger than him, who also excels in twisting throws, he scored 32 first-class hundreds.
But the fact that Middlesex&#39;s Shah managed only ten runs in two quarters in the Test at Lord&#39;s at home in May against the West Indies, and the fact that Vaughan, who was fighting for his inclusion in the next game, met with immediate opposition from the selectors, seems it reduced the tenacity in him that was still clearly visible in Bombay.
In contrast, Essex&#39;s all-round talent is a jovial and unsurpassed player.
There is nothing to upset him on the cricket field, but his behavior off the field was well described when he overturned a four-wheeler belonging to the team&#39;s car sponsor, Volkswagen, at an exhibition.
He received minor injuries and was probably shocked. Still, the first thing he did afterwards was pick up his (sponsored) Vodafone phone and call his team-mate Alastair Cook, who was watching from a distance, to ask: &quot;Did you see that?&quot;
Bopara is a better sideline player with classics. His sliding mid-steps create an advantageous throwing angle for him, and his strikes are confident and skillful.
Choosing the right person is one thing, choosing the right moment is another.
Perhaps this is the true art of selection.
Personally, I&#39;d give Bopara the chance now, which isn&#39;t to say I don&#39;t think Shah wouldn&#39;t be outstanding if, as the Ceylon tea leaves suggest, he&#39;s the one playing at the weekend.
