Venus is Earth&#39;s evil twin
Despite its harsh atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously assumed: The European &quot;Venus Express&quot; spacecraft discovered lightning in its atmosphere and wind vortices similar to those that occur on Earth in winter in its polar circles.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that lightning occurs on Venus.
The European &quot;Venus Express&quot; spacecraft provided evidence - it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning that occurs on Venus spreads from cloud to cloud at an altitude of approximately 56 kilometers, Christopher Russel, a colleague from the University of California, Los Angeles, reports in the columns of the scientific magazine &quot;Nature&quot;.
According to the famous &quot;primordial soup theory&quot;, the formation of life on Earth was caused by lightning: According to the theory, thunderstorms started reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: &quot;If there ever was life there, it must have been very early,&quot; explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Currently, living organisms can hardly exist on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and the temperature values sometimes reach 500 degrees.
&quot;Venus may be Earth&#39;s twin from hell, but it&#39;s still Earth&#39;s twin,&quot; Russel said.
The main question of the Esa mission is why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, is on a completely different development path.
The launch of the &quot;Venus Express&quot; in November 2005 was a milestone in Venus research, because since the beginning of the nineties, no probe had been on its way specifically to search for this planet.
According to the researchers, the latest research results presented in several &quot;Nature&quot; articles prove more than just the uniqueness of Venus within the Solar System.
&quot;They also show that the neighboring planet&#39;s similarity to Earth is greater than we first assumed,&quot; Esa said.
In addition to the well-known North Pole vortex, the researchers also discovered an even faster-moving cloud vortex at the South Pole.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents of the Earth&#39;s winter hemisphere, claims the research group led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of the Solar System has almost the same mass as the Earth, and with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers it is almost the same size as the Earth.
The celestial body, also called the Evening Star, orbits the Sun in just 225 days,
however, it rotates much more slowly around its own sun: One Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus&#39; surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius combined with a pressure of 92 bar hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that both planets formed under completely similar conditions.
Water accumulated on both of them, which remained as an ocean on Earth, while on Venus it left for the universe.
And while on Earth carbon dioxide is bound in carbonate rocks, on Venus it makes up most of the atmosphere.
