However, the film &quot;Vadaszat&quot; and the German production &quot;Mörderischer Frieden&quot;, which also started screening this week, continue the endless series of failed films about the Balkan war, even in spite of this trump card.
The movie &quot;Mörderischer Frieden&quot; doesn&#39;t have to be wasted: The movie is about two German soldiers serving in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt), who save a Serbian woman from snipers in Kosovo, and one of them even suddenly falls in love with her.
While it&#39;s welcome that for once the Serbs aren&#39;t portrayed as the sole cause of all evil, the movie, which carries the shallowness of TV movies, gets lost too quickly in the gunfights and action-packed scenes.
It has a &quot;Cobra 11&quot; character - with war instead of a highway.
On the other hand, in the case of &quot;Vadaszat&quot;, it is possible to examine as an example why not a single really good film about the Balkan war has been made.
The story of the three US war correspondents who set out to find the main Serbian war criminal named &quot;Fox&quot; could have become a new &quot;Apocalypse Now&quot; in a different era with a different director and screenwriter (both in the personal union of Richard Shepard).
After all, the stories show a surprising similarity: In both cases, small groups take to the forest to accomplish what the army is unable to do - and in both cases, the journey to madness is rounded off.
One of the reasons &quot;The Hunt&quot; fails is that it simply doesn&#39;t let Simon Hunt be the down-to-earth cynic he&#39;s made out to be at the beginning.
No, and as an encore in the script, he even has a romantic relationship with a Muslim Bosnian woman who is later murdered.
The &quot;Hunting&quot; slips away for good when, in the last five minutes of the film, the reporters achieve what NATO, the CIA, and all the world&#39;s bounty hunters have not been able to do in five years: They capture the war criminal and then hand him over to Mohammedan. to Bosnians for the purpose of just revenge.
This is so bad that one would rather go to the International Tribunal in The Hague for a crime against the logic of cinema.
Yet the film&#39;s purpose is profoundly human.
He intends to expose the fact that Karadzic and Mladic are still at large, and that he suspects the Americans and the French (who are said to be exceptionally united on this point) of not continuing the pursuit intensively enough due to secret political deals.
But good and evil are sometimes so similar that one is reminded of a famous Brecht poem.
In it, the poet writes the following about the wooden mask depicting an Asian demon on his desk: &quot;I stare with compassion at the throbbing vein on his temple, which tells me how tiring it is to be bad.&quot;
Movies like &quot;The Hunt&quot; have the same oversized masks in the shape of human heads, but they show how tiring it is to be good.
This problem is not limited to the genre of films about the Balkan War.
It was recently reported in the newspaper that all the Hollywood movies about Iraq were abject flops.
We can add: There has not yet been a single good film about South Africa.
It is almost always valid: If a star wanders through the world&#39;s hotbeds of crisis or minefields, something like &quot;Paths of Freedom&quot; with Patricia Arquette, &quot;Without Borders&quot; with Angelina Jolie or &quot;Blood Diamond&quot; with Leonardo Di Caprio comes out of it.
It is possible that these conflicts are simply too close in time.
After all, decades had to pass before Hollywood was able to make a good film about the Holocaust with the film &quot;Schindler&#39;s List&quot;.
It is likely that some of the films will still mature - since the works about the Vietnam War, which are now considered classics, e.g. The films &quot;The Deer Hunter&quot;, &quot;Apocalypse Now&quot; or &quot;Full Metal Jacket&quot; were not unanimously celebrated as masterpieces in their time.
But it&#39;s possible that these days, when every mass murder comes to our homes in real time, right through two screens, we simply know too much about the world&#39;s conflicts.
And it robs screenwriters of the kind of reality-bending that is needed to tell good stories.
After all, &quot;To be or not to be&quot; or &quot;The Dictator&quot; succeeded so well because Lubitsch and Chaplin did not yet know how terrible the Nazi regime really was.
Maybe you shouldn&#39;t strive for the good if you want to make a good film.
Perhaps we should place ourselves in the sarcastically distant artistic vision of the novelist Lawrence Norfolk.
When asked about the parallels between his historical novel &quot;The Lemprière Lexicon&quot; and the Balkan War, he replied: &quot;It&#39;s just that certain things never change.
Big cities will always be terribly dangerous, people will always be killed in horrible ways, and Yugoslavia will always be at war.&quot;
