These are not Warhol&#39;s chests
Anyone who connects the concepts of Sweden and wooden crates is thinking of Ikea, not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wooden chests made in Sweden cast a dark shadow on the catalog of Warhol&#39;s works.
Most of the ninety-four &quot;Stockholm-type&quot; Brillo Boxes listed here are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper &quot;Expressen&quot; cast doubt on the authenticity of Andy Warhol&#39;s 1968 Brillo Boxes a few months ago, the internal investigation of Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now reached a sobering result: The six &quot; Brillo Box&quot; copy - and most probably also the majority of the hundred other &quot;Stockholm-type&quot; Brillo Boxes on the international art market.
The prehistory is a long and complicated, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial stunts.
Warhol created his first &quot;Brillo Boxes&quot; in New York in 1964 - painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the &quot;Brillo&quot; soap powder cardboard box.
At an exhibition of his works held at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol&#39;s consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard were exhibited: These (for reasons of cost savings) did not come from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not about works of art, but about their templates, simple exhibition pieces.
At the same time, in 1968, Warhol gave permission for some Brillo paintings to be produced in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time now speak of around fifteen such chests, which at the time, as authenticated Original-Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Boxes, went down in the history of art and auctions under the designation &quot;Stockholm type&quot;.
Some have been auctioned for over $100,000.
The problem, however, is that Pontus Hultén, the legendary museum director, later falsely claimed that around one hundred wooden chests were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén&#39;s 105 chests were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
However, by this time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, Chief Curator of Moderna Museet, in addition to the six Brillo Boxes owned by the museum, also examined three privately owned Swedish boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: The pressed chipboards were first primed and sanded, then white oil paint was applied with a brush .
On the other hand, the structure of the copies from 1990 reveals that the paint was applied directly to the chipboard with a paint roller without priming - moreover, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic paint.
&quot;These boxes have not been authenticated by the artist, so they should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol&#39;s Brillo Boxes,&quot; says Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet: &quot;Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York decides otherwise, Moderna Museet will classify the six chests in its collection as replicas/exhibition material.&quot;
Of course, the Authentication Board already announced in June that it was investigating the &quot;serious allegations&quot; made in connection with soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, they have been shrouded in relentless silence.
